  "signature": "ed25519:90fb2342da91797b798ca7c08bd4792d5061ce841f43a194b9ae030071b039236f9813c530227783a37d5fd5be7cdb60a09203218666adb0ef554083bb6e140e",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-sqa",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Mechanical 2023 R1 is a commercially validated FEA solver with documented V&V history. Software quality assurance records include version control logs, regression test suite results (>2400 benchmark cases), and change management documentation. Installation qualification and operational qualification records are on file. Gradation 3 achieved: solver is commercially available with published verification documentation and internal IQ/OQ records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-ncv",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification performed using ANSYS built-in benchmark suite and three independent patch-test problems relevant to contact mechanics in orthopedic applications. Analytical solutions for Hertzian contact, cantilever beam bending, and axisymmetric pressure vessel problems reproduced within 0.3% of closed-form solutions. Nonlinear contact algorithm verified against published NAFEMS benchmarks LE1 and LE10. Gradation 3 achieved: independent benchmark problems solved with documented comparison to analytical solutions."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-disc",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh convergence study performed using three mesh refinement levels (coarse: 182k elements, medium: 487k elements, fine: 1.21M elements) following ASME V&V 10.1 Richardson extrapolation methodology. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for peak interface micromotion: GCI_fine = 1.8%, GCI_medium = 6.4%; apparent order of convergence p = 1.94, consistent with quadratic tetrahedral elements. Asymptotic range confirmed (GCI ratio = 1.02). Production mesh uses fine discretization. Gradation 4 achieved: formal GCI analysis with asymptotic convergence confirmation and extrapolated solution reported."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-tc",
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions are documented in calibrated test protocol NTK-TP-2023-04. Loading conditions replicate ISO 14243-1 gait cycle forces and moments applied via servo-hydraulic test frame. Cadaveric tibiae (n=8, ages 55–72) were CT-scanned pre-test to characterize bone mineral density distribution. Temperature (22 ± 1 °C), humidity, and specimen preparation protocols are fully documented. All measurement instrumentation (LVDT micromotion sensors, load cells) are traceable to NIST standards with current calibration certificates. Gradation 3 achieved: test conditions fully documented with traceable calibration records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-oc",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison metrics applied: mean absolute error, normalized RMSE, and Pearson correlation coefficient computed for peak micromotion across all 6 loading scenarios and 8 cadaveric specimens (48 data points). Prediction intervals computed from combined model and experimental uncertainty. All FEA predictions fall within ±2 standard deviations of experimental mean. Feature validation (spatial distribution of micromotion hotspots) confirmed by visual comparison of FEA contour plots against DIC measurement maps. Gradation 3 achieved: multiple quantitative metrics with uncertainty-bounded comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-rqoi",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI — peak bone-implant interface micromotion — is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of aseptic loosening through published literature (Pilliar et al. 1986; Engh et al. 1992). The 150 µm threshold is grounded in histological evidence for fibrous encapsulation onset. Secondary QoIs (contact area, von Mises stress in tibial tray, cortical strain distribution) are each mapped to specific failure modes identified in the device risk analysis. QoI hierarchy documented in assessment plan NAG-AP-2024-01. Gradation 3 achieved: QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes with literature-supported thresholds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-rvac",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were designed to span the COU applicability domain: loading scenarios cover ISO 14243-1 gait cycle, stair ascent, and chair rise (6 scenarios bracketing clinical use); bone density range of cadaveric specimens (BMD 0.32–0.89 g/cm²) encompasses target patient population. Implant geometry used in validation matches production geometry within manufacturing tolerances. Validation domain map documented in NAG-VM-2024-02, confirming no extrapolation beyond validated domain for intended COU. Gradation 3 achieved: validation domain formally mapped and confirmed to encompass COU applicability space."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-nse",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence monitored at each load step: force residual < 1×10⁻⁴, displacement residual < 1×10⁻⁵, and energy residual < 1×10⁻⁶ enforced. Newton-Raphson iteration history reviewed for all 48 simulation runs; no divergence or non-physical oscillation observed. Contact status stabilization confirmed by monitoring contact force sum across load increments. Round-off error assessed via double-precision arithmetic verification. Gradation 3 achieved: formal convergence criteria documented with residual monitoring across all production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-ue",
      "rationale": "Model use governed by documented simulation protocol NAG-SP-2024-03 covering mesh generation, material assignment, boundary condition application, and post-processing. Independent technical review performed by second analyst not involved in model development; reviewer confirmed boundary condition fidelity, material property mapping, and QoI extraction methodology. Discrepancies identified during review (3 minor annotation errors) resolved and documented in review log NAG-RL-2024-03. Gradation 3 achieved: independent peer review with documented resolution of findings."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-mf",
      "rationale": "Model form selection justified through literature review and sensitivity analysis. Bone modeled as heterogeneous linear elastic continuum with density-modulus relationships from Keyak et al. (1994); justification: strain rates in gait loading are below viscoelastic transition frequency. Titanium tibial tray modeled as isotropic linear elastic (E = 114 GPa, ν = 0.34). Bone-implant interface modeled with frictional contact (µ = 0.42, from Shirazi-Adl et al.); sensitivity to ±20% friction coefficient variation assessed (peak micromotion change < 9%). Model form assumptions documented in NAG-MF-2024-01 with explicit justification for each simplification. Gradation 3 achieved: model form assumptions explicitly documented with sensitivity-based justification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-mi",
      "rationale": "Probabilistic sensitivity analysis (Monte Carlo, n=1000 samples) performed on 12 input parameters including bone density distribution, friction coefficient, implant positioning tolerance, and loading magnitude. Sobol sensitivity indices computed; top 3 inputs (bone density, axial load magnitude, implant varus/valgus alignment) account for 78% of output variance. Input probability distributions derived from published population studies and manufacturing tolerance specifications. Input uncertainty propagation documented in NAG-UQ-2024-04. Gradation 3 achieved: formal sensitivity analysis with documented input uncertainty distributions and propagation results."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-ts",
      "rationale": "Eight cadaveric tibiae used for validation represent the target patient population (age 55–72, mixed sex: 5F/3M, BMD range 0.32–0.89 g/cm²). Sample size justified by a priori power analysis targeting 80% power to detect 25 µm mean difference in peak micromotion (α=0.05). Specimen characterization includes DXA BMD, micro-CT trabecular architecture, and histological assessment of cortical quality. Specimen preparation, storage, and testing sequence documented in NAG-TP-2024-02. No outliers excluded without documented justification. Gradation 3 achieved: sample population characterized with documented representativeness to COU patient population."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-ortho-ac-eip",
      "rationale": "Specimen-specific FEA models constructed from CT scans of each cadaveric tibia used in validation experiments, ensuring geometric fidelity between simulation and physical test. Material properties assigned using subject-specific CT-derived density maps (Hounsfield unit to modulus conversion validated separately). Loading conditions in simulation replicate experimental setup including fixture compliance (measured and incorporated as boundary spring stiffness). Input parameter equivalency formally assessed in NAG-EIP-2024-05 using parameter-by-parameter mapping table. Residual discrepancies (e.g., soft tissue exclusion) assessed via sensitivity analysis and found to contribute < 5% to peak micromotion prediction. Gradation 3 achieved: specimen-specific models with formal input equivalency mapping and residual discrepancy assessment."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-ortho-cou1-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-ortho-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (tibial tray fixation FEA, Class II TKA, MRL 3) is accepted based on the following structured evidence review: (1) All 13 credibility factors assessed at or above required levels for MRL 3; achieved levels meet or exceed required levels in all cases, with Discretization Error and Numerical Solver Error achieving Gradation 4 and 3 respectively against requirements of 3 and 2. (2) Three independent validation results (cadaveric micromotion, cortical strain, contact pressure) collectively demonstrate model predictive accuracy within 15% normalized error across all QoIs, with uncertainty quantification links established for each. (3) Provenance chain is complete: all validation results link back to foundational experimental datasets (ds01–ds04) via documented activity records and uncertainty quantification nodes. (4) Sensitivity and uncertainty analyses confirm that model predictions are robust to input variability within the COU applicability domain; no input parameter drives prediction error beyond acceptance thresholds. (5) The validation domain map confirms no extrapolation beyond the validated space for the intended COU. (6) Independent technical review completed with all findings resolved. The model is credible for its intended use: identifying worst-case fixation failure conditions for the Class II cementless TKA tibial tray under MRL 3 requirements.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
